{
  "doc_id": "28507",
  "text": "Previous studies reported inconsistencies in respect to MRI based volumetric changes in the brain and affected regions in the brain [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . In the current study, we were not able to attribute any VBM or VBQ brain or brainstem differences unambiguously to chronic sensorimotor complete SCI. The median time since injury was around 12 years in the analyzed cohort. Only one other study [CITATION_7] analyzed a comparable SCI group in respect to injury severity and time since injury. However, our data do not support their finding of extensive reduced GM volumes in motor and non-motor regions of the brain related to SCI. We identified a correlation of brain volume reductions in respective regions only related to age (statistical significant covariate associated with smaller GM volumes; used as nuisance variable in our study), which has been consistently shown in previous studies not related to SCI [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . Lack of statistical power is also unlikely to explain the deviating findings. 14 SCI subjects were investigated in the present study, whereas 13 [CITATION_11] ), 10 (Freund et al., 2011 ), 15 (Wrigley et al., 2009a , and 17 [CITATION_12] ) SCI subjects were enrolled in previous MRI studies.",
